text:
Well this game is incredible. I already knew about the ending, so I was watching all the little tricks it did to connect these girls to the characters. All those minigames to make them compete with each other and to make the characters compete too. All the events where both are needed to make them seem closer. The heart string pulls to make the characters seem real. Even if they hadn't picked the 'right' characters that fit them, that ending would've hurt.

Then these two went and made it even better because they seem so close. Joking, working together, coincidentally syncing with the characters. Like, ow. That ending stung. Great job Ame! Gura!

(Sorry this comment focuses more on the game itself. This was my first time experiencing it beyond mentions in videos about co op games, and I'm interested in game design, so I couldn't help but nerd out a little seeing details like that.)

text: Something I always find weird in a story where someone robs a safe is when the alarm goes off even though they used the combination to open it. It could make sense in a more modern setting, I imagine you can set it up so your security system has to be deactivated before you even open your safe normally to be extra safe. This is set in like the 60s or 70s, so I figure the alarm would also be deactivated when you put in the code. I mean, I'm no expert on security systems, but I figure you wouldn't want the alarm going off every time you open the safe, which you'd do daily to put your store's daily earnings in, cause if you forget to deactivate the alarm first you'll now have to wait for the cops to show up and tell them it was an accident, probably show them your ID and proof that it's your business, it'd just be such a hassle. It seems more convenient to have using the code not set off any alarm, or just leave it off until you close up and leave so anyone breaking in to open it when no one should be around sets the alarm off.

text:
I don‚Äôt know how to feel about the ending. On one hand, it‚Äôs an amazingly bittersweet ending, that uses the relationship you built up through the entire game to sock you in the face. It‚Äôs an ending that can only work as well as it does in this specific type of game. But on the other hand, it feels so tacked on.
The entirety of the game prior to the plane landing and the portion after feel like completely different stories. And I guess that‚Äôs the point, but it makes it so that the game basically ended on the plane ride home. The story is wrapped up, the main villain is defeated, and all the character arcs come to a close. But then they shoehorn in the ‚ÄúVincent is a cop‚Äù storybeat out of nowhere and force in the entire fourth act from thin air(yes, fourth act, since killing Harvey closed off the third act). And to make matters worse, the game forces the two to kill each other off. But that doesn‚Äôt even need to happen. Vincent could literally just tell Leo he‚Äôll turn a blind eye and let him escape, since apparantly Leo can avoid the entire rest of the city‚Äôs police officers, cruisers, and helicopters completely fine. Both characters live. The end. It isn‚Äôt nearly as sad, but it makes a lot more sense. 
And to top it all off, Vincent being a police officer makes no sense. A major portion of the game is built around how both of their faces are stuck on the front of the local newspaper, assumedly throughout the entire state. Even if Vincent is an Avengers level hero known amongst all the police, citizens will still get only know him from there and get scared of him, causing massive panic and issues.


Basically, the ending is like if Goku and Piccolo returned from Namek, and Goku suddenly reports Piccolo to the authorities since he tried to destroy the world before. Then one of them kills the other, and the story comes to a close.

text:
This... was one of the most bittersweet streams I've ever watched. On one hand, we have Ame and Gura having teetee moments like the letter scene (that one made me blush for real)
But on the other hand, we have the betrayal scene which I didn't expect at all (I expected something bc of chat, but not this...) It hurt even more when you had to make a choice between Leo or Vincent, who both had important people in their lives and have built a good relationship with each other. 
...
It's been a long time since I last cried because of a game and I didn't expect this one, of all games, to make me cry. 
Ame and Gura's chemistry made it more definitive as the characters' traits fit them so well. Gura was even on the verge of tearing up, hearing Ame act as Vincent.
...
Personally, I enjoyed the ending. Even though it made me cry, this was one of the games that had a more realistic ending perse. Most happy endings for any form of media, be it books or games, are rather idealistic for me. There are no fairy tale endings in real life.
So seeing an ending that's different from most, made me feel somewhat satisfied to an extent.

Thank you, Gura and Ame for an amazing stream. I hope you two can play more great, story-driven games in the future.

Also, GurAme is confirmed. 2:35:00

text:
TL;DR: It's a love letter to 80's movies and it's made to be dumb and fun, not hold up perfectly to scrutiny. 
¬†@omnilisk279¬† I think this may have been on purpose, the plot itself not holding up to too much scrutiny. The game, to me, and I may be wrong, feels quite a lot like a love letter to 80's movies and prison breakout things. They use all the tropes they could get away with to do so, as well. The toilet being able to just be pried away? The plumbing would get in the way of that. But it's a worn trope and it's fun, so they used it. The coat hanger zipline? It'd break under the weight of a grown man(Probably, don't quote me), or it would snap under the friction. Or both. But it's a fun trope. Also, why are there HANGERS in a prison guard tower? Because it's a fun trope. 

The game isn't about holding up perfectly, in the same way that those movies and tropes aren't. They're based on fun, and entertainment. It feels like you're being unfair to the game by saying that it's executed poorly, because as far as I can tell, it's executed astoundingly. If you described the plot of the game to me and asked me to guess when it came out, leaving out that it's a game, I'd assume it's a fun 80's movie with a solid plot twist, especially for the time. And that's what it feels like it's supposed to be. Does the plot hold up if you look at it for more than a couple minutes? No. But it can be fun to poke holes in it, in the same way that it can be fun to poke holes in the movies I keep talking about. For instance, in the Terminator, why didn't Skynet send the Terminator right into Sarah Connor's house, the most effective place for it to be? Because it's no fun if they go for the smartest direct thing.

There is one point you are flat out incorrect on, that being the idea that Vincent would or could aim for the leg or go for a non-fatal option when holding Leo at gunpoint. I've never been in a gunfight, but I do know that when you're trained as an officer, you're trained to aim for center mass. Vincent knows that Leo is not gonna stop, even if he's being held at gunpoint. He's gonna charge you and smite God while he's at it, and Vincent would  react based on his instincts and training, not on deep thought. Aiming to kill Leo makes leagues more sense than if he had aimed for somewhere non-fatal, because he's defending his own life.


I hope this doesn't come across as condescending or arrogant, it just feels like you're being resoundingly negative, and helping to be a bit more fair to a game that wasn't made by the specifications you're holding it to is all I mean to do. I hope my points make sense.

text:
¬†@omnilisk279¬† I agree that most of the plot points you mentioned are shaky writing, but non-lethal shooting in that situation is extremely difficult. You mentioned training; well, police are trained to shoot center mass btw. Anyone who receives training from a shooting instructor will be taught to shoot center mass. Aiming anywhere else greatly increases your chance to miss, ESPECIALLY in high pressure scenarios. Try aiming a gun when you're tired or clearly agitated. You'll find that it's incredibly difficult and if you were to consider the other conditions of the situation Vincent was in, that just adds to the difficulty. He's aiming with one hand (fully loaded MP5 weighs around 8 lbs/3 kg) so he can't actually sight his target and Leo's close enough to pose a threat. Aiming for a non-lethal shot in that position is already almost impossible and hitting one without properly aiming would just be incredibly lucky.

Plot holes aside, it's still enjoyable. They built up the dynamic Vincent and Leo had well enough that the betrayal was still painful to experience.

If we're dragging realism into this, you don't shoot to maim or incapacitate in real life. It's too difficult to do in a clutch moment, a wounded perp can still attack you, and even if you do hit them in a limb it can still be fatal anyway. You shoot to kill or not at all. Shooting into a human shield situation is also more risk than it's worth. You risk either not killing the perp instantly, or gravely injuring the hostage with your own gunfire.

Emily didn't have her gun. Leo took it from her. She would've had no other option than to radio for backup, and it would've taken time for said backup to arrive, enough time for Leo and Vincent to finish their shootout.

And since we're complaining about a lack of realism, the entire game should've ended before they even got out of prison because humans have peripheral vision and can see farther than 10 feet in front of their face, so any of the stealth sections would've been impossible.
